## Conclusion and Opinion

The ability to read and write critically is not merely an academic skill but a vital competency for navigating the complexities of modern life. Informed by the reviewed literature, it is clear that critical literacy is foundational to personal empowerment, societal engagement, and the maintenance of democratic values. The digital age, characterized by an abundance of information and misinformation alike, makes critical literacy indispensable.

Governments, educational institutions, and communities must prioritize the development of critical reading and writing skills for all individuals. This includes integrating critical literacy into curricula, promoting digital literacy frameworks that emphasize critical mindsets, and fostering environments where questioning and reflective thinking are encouraged.

In my opinion, without widespread critical literacy, societies risk falling prey to misinformation, manipulation, and social fragmentation. Conversely, a population equipped with critical reading and writing skills is better positioned to contribute to equitable, informed, and resilient communities. Therefore, critical literacy should be regarded as a fundamental human right and a cornerstone of education in the 21st century.

